        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>This proposal aims at detecting the CO(3-2) line redshifted to 103.09
GHz observable with the ALMA receiver band 3. The remaining bandwidth
will be used for mapping the continuum. The target coordinates are on
the quasar itself with the offset to the DLA galaxy host derived from
our SINFONI data.

Using the H-alpha luminosity measured in our SINFONI observations, we
derive the star formation rate (SFR) assuming the Kennicutt (1998)
flux conversion corrected to a Chabrier (2003) IMF. For the galaxy
host responsible for the DLA toward Q2222-0026, we measure a SFR of 17
solar masses per year corresponding to a dust-corrected SFR of 37
solar masses per year (the dust correction is estimated from the flux
ratio of H-alpha and H-beta). Based on the SFR-L_FIR relation of
Kennicutt (1998), this translates to L_FIR=2 \times 10^11
L_sum. Using the CO-FIR correlation (Solomon &amp; van den Bout 2005), we
derive an expected minimum CO flux of L_CO=4 \times 10^9 K km/s
pc^2. We thus should reach total molecular mass of the order 1-2
\times 10^10 M_sun assuming a galactic H_2-CO conversion factor.

We therefore expect a flux of about 740 mJy km/s or a flux density of
5 mJy for a 150 km/s line (as indicated from H-alpha). Using the ALMA
sensitivity calculator with 34 antennas, we get an rms noise 0.5 mJy
in 20 km/s channels in 21 min on the target, corresponding to a total
observing time including calibration of 35 min. This set-up will
provide a SNR of about 10, which is needed for our scientific
goals. We have checked that the background quasar that has a small
angular separation from our target is fainter than this limit, using a
non-detection at this sky position in the FIRST survey. We therefore
expect it to be faint at millimeter wavelengths as well.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
