    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>A big challenge in the study of galaxy formation is to relate the
neutral, molecular gas and the stars in galaxies. Quasar absorbers are
galaxies selected purely by HI gas and are associated with the
reservoir of fuel available for star formation. Star formation is
believed to occur in molecular clouds, so one would logically expect
that many DLAs contain molecular gas. Here, we propose to observe a
unique target, the galaxy host of the z=2.35 intervening quasar
absorber with the highest measured SFR, with known HI column density
and metallicity from absorption studies, HII metallicity and
kinematics from integral field unit H-alpha emission line
observations. This proposal aims at detecting CO(3-2) line redshifted
to 103.09 GHz. The goal is to measure and map the molecular component
and thus estimate the total gas mass of the system. Altogether, this
information will allow us to draw a clear picture of the dynamics of
the neutral, ionised and molecular gas in the same z~2 object. The
results of the proposed project would provide a stunning example of
the impact of ALMA on cosmological studies and illustrate the great
prospects at hand when the full array is commissioned.
</prp:abstract>
